== What the Microbiome Is

The human microbiome refers to the trillions of bacteria, viruses, fungi, and other microorganisms that live in and on our bodies. The gut microbiome—the collection of microbes in the intestinal tract—is especially important.

=== Why the Microbiome Matters

Your gut microbiome plays essential roles in:

- _Immunity_: Up to 70% of your immune system resides in the gut. Gut bacteria train immune cells to distinguish friend from foe, preventing autoimmune reactions and allergies.
- _Digestion_: Gut bacteria break down complex carbohydrates and fiber, producing short-chain fatty acids that nourish gut cells and regulate metabolism.
- _Metabolism_: The microbiome influences weight, blood sugar regulation, and fat storage.
- _Mental health_: The gut-brain axis links gut bacteria to mood, anxiety, and even cognitive development. Gut bacteria produce neurotransmitters like serotonin and GABA.
- _Disease protection_: A diverse, balanced microbiome protects against pathogens, reduces inflammation, and may lower the risk of chronic diseases.

=== Babies Start Sterile

Unlike adults, babies are born essentially sterile—free of bacteria. This means the very first microbes they encounter have an outsized influence on their developing microbiome. These early colonizers shape immune programming, metabolic pathways, and lifelong health trajectories.

The first 1,000 days of life (from conception to age 2) represent a _critical window_ for microbiome establishment. Disruptions during this period can have lasting consequences.

